What is this analysis?

This notebook is for selecting a game and identifying its most comparable games using data from boardgamegeek.com. I use a dimension reduction method (PCA) to understand the main points of variation in data from boardgamegeek and then compute the Euclidean distance between all games using their values on the first ten principal components. The current approach for computing the Euclidean distance weighs each component equally; I plan to explore a change to this in the future by using a different measure of distance, as we would reasonably expect some components to be more important than others.

Note: The analysis does not make use of a games number of ratings, average, or geek average, but instead looks only at it a games categories, mechanics, playing time, player count, and complexity.

Examining PCA Variable Loadings

What explains a games score on each principal component?

To gain a better understanding of these principal components, we can look at the loadings for the variables in the dataset. These are the the contributions of each variable to the ten components used in computing the distance between games. Large loadings (either positive or negative) for a variable indicate that there is a strong relationship between that variable and the component.

For instance, on the first principal component (PC1), time per player, average weight, and playing time have the highest positive loadings, while party game and max players have negative loadings. This indicates that this component seems to map to a games complexity - longer, more complex games will have high positive scores on this component while simpler, shorter, party games with lots of players will have low scores.
